{"timestamp": "2026-05-28 12:45:28,241", "level": "INFO", "logger": "flow.validation", "module": "logging_config", "function": "log_validation_result", "line": 185, "message": "{\"timestamp\": \"2026-05-28T12:45:28.241828\", \"task_id\": \"unknown\", \"task_objective\": \"Generate technical interview questions tailored to the extracted job requirements and candidate profile.\", \"result\": \"```text\\nRound: Technical\\nQuestion: Describe your experience with distributed systems. What are some of the challenges you've faced when designing and implementing them, and how did you overcome them?\\nCompetency Tested: Distributed Systems, Problem-Solving\\nIdeal Answer Indicators: Demonstrates a deep understanding of distributed systems concepts (e.g., consistency, fault tolerance, scalability). Provides specific examples of challenges faced (e.g., data consistency, network latency, concurrency) ...\", \"validation_type\": \"text\", \"status\": \"completed\", \"feedback\": \"here are some feedbacks:\\n1. The questions provided are generic and not specifically tailored to the extracted job requirements or the candidate’s profile.\\n2. We need to reference the specific technologies and competencies from the job description (e.g., Spring Boot, Kubernetes, Kafka, CI/CD) and the candidate’s resume (e.g., Java, event-driven systems, AWS, Terraform).\\n3. Add a few more targeted questions (e.g., microservices design, container orchestration, DevOps practices).\\n4. Maintain the required format: plain text with sections for Question, Competency Tested, Ideal Answer Indicators, and Follow-up Probes.\\n\\nhere are the changes:\\n\\nRound: Technical  \\nQuestion: Describe a Spring Boot microservice you designed and implemented. What were the core components, and how did you ensure modularity and scalability?  \\nCompetency Tested: Java, Spring Boot, Microservices Architecture, Design Patterns  \\nIdeal Answer Indicators: Candidate explains the overall service responsibilities, use of layered architecture (controllers, services, repositories), design patterns (Factory, Strategy), use of Spring Cloud modules (Config, Eureka), and how they scaled via horizontal pods or instance autoscaling.  \\nFollow-up Probes: How did you handle inter-service communication? What trade-offs did you consider when choosing synchronous vs. asynchronous calls?\\n\\nRound: Technical  \\nQuestion: Walk me through your approach to containerizing applications with Docker and orchestrating them on Kubernetes. Include how you configured deployments, services, and managed rolling updates.  \\nCompetency Tested: Docker, Kubernetes, DevOps, Continuous Deployment  \\nIdeal Answer Indicators: Describes writing Dockerfiles (multi-stage builds), creating Kubernetes manifests (Deployment, Service, ConfigMap, Secret), using Helm charts or Kustomize, setting liveness/readiness probes, and configuring rolling update strategies.  \\nFollow-up Probes: How do you manage environment-specific configurations? How do you troubleshoot pod failures?\\n\\nRound: Technical  \\nQuestion: Explain how you implemented an event-driven architecture using Apache Kafka (or AWS SNS/SQS). Describe topic design, message schema, and how you ensured reliability and ordering.  \\nCompetency Tested: Event-Driven Systems, Messaging, Data Modeling  \\nIdeal Answer Indicators: Discusses defining Kafka topics/partitions, using Avro/JSON schema registry, configuring producer acknowledgments, consumer groups, idempotent consumers, and strategies for schema evolution.  \\nFollow-up Probes: How do you handle poison messages? What strategies do you use to replay or back-populate events?\\n\\nRound: Technical  \\nQuestion: Detail a CI/CD pipeline you built using Jenkins (or GitHub Actions). How did you integrate code quality, security scans, and automated deployments?  \\nCompetency Tested: DevOps, CI/CD, Automation, Security  \\nIdeal Answer Indicators: Outlines pipeline stages (checkout, build, test, static code analysis, vulnerability scanning, container build, deploy to staging/production), use of Jenkinsfiles or workflows, integration with SonarQube/Snyk, and rollback procedures.  \\nFollow-up Probes: How do you handle pipeline failures? How do you secure your pipeline credentials and secrets?\\n\\nRound: Technical  \\nQuestion: Describe your experience deploying infrastructure as code with Terraform (or CloudFormation). How did you manage state and handle drift?  \\nCompetency Tested: Infrastructure as Code, Cloud Engineering, AWS  \\nIdeal Answer Indicators: Mentions writing HCL modules, remote state backends (S3 with DynamoDB locking), use of workspaces, handling resource dependencies, and periodic drift detection with terraform plan.  \\nFollow-up Probes: How do you test Terraform changes before applying? How do you manage secrets in IaC?\\n\\nRound: Technical  \\nQuestion: Discuss a challenging performance issue you encountered in a Java application. How did you profile, diagnose, and resolve the bottleneck?  \\nCompetency Tested: Java Performance Tuning, Profiling, Diagnostics  \\nIdeal Answer Indicators: Talks about using profilers (VisualVM, JProfiler), GC logs analysis, thread dumps, identifying hotspots (e.g., synchronized blocks, database queries), and applying optimizations (connection pooling, caching, query tuning).  \\nFollow-up Probes: How did you measure improvement? What metrics did you monitor in production?\\n\\nRound: Technical  \\nQuestion: Explain your strategy for securing a RESTful microservice. Cover authentication, authorization, encryption, and audit logging.  \\nCompetency Tested: API Security, OAuth2/JWT, Best Practices  \\nIdeal Answer Indicators: Demonstrates use of OAuth2/JWT tokens, role-based access control, TLS enforcement, input validation, rate limiting, and centralized audit logging.  \\nFollow-up Probes: How do you manage token revocation? How do you rotate certificates and secrets securely?\"}"}
